The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Parekh to continue as HDFC chairman
                                                                                                               Parekh to continue as HDFC chairman
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                       Parekh: Term extended                          
	Mumbai, Feb. 25: HDFC chairman Deepak Parekh is not retiring at the end of this month and will remain the executive chairman till December.        
	The board of directors of the corporation has reappointed Deepak Parekh as the managing director (designated as chairman) with effect from March 1, 2009 up to the close of business hours on December 31, 2009, subject to the approval of the members of the corporation at the ensuing annual general meeting, HDFC informed the stock exchanges today.         
	Speculations were rife about Parekh relinquishing charge at the end of this month.         
	It is learnt that the board of HDFC had urged Parekh to extend his term.         
	The company might announce the appointment of a new executive chairman by November this year.         
	Parekh  a fellow of the Institute of Chartered Accountants (England amp; Wales)  joined the corporation in a senior management position in 1978. He was inducted as a whole-time director in 1985 and appointed chairman in 1993.         
	Recently, he was appointed by the government on the board of crisis-ridden Satyam Computer Services.         
	Highly respected in the business and financial community, Parekh has been successful in making HDFC the leader in housing finance despite tough competition.        
	HDFC had posted a 15.73 per cent decline in profit after tax at Rs 546.83 crore for the third quarter ended December 31, 2008 compared with Rs 648.93 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous year.        
	The companys total income rose 42.54 per cent to Rs 2,917.77 crore from Rs 2,046.93 crore a year ago.        
	The companys share price fell 34.60 points, or 2.68 per cent, to close at Rs 1,254.40 on the Bombay Stock Exchange today.                                                                                                                                       
